INSURANCE COMPARISON PLATFORM
SECTION 9.5
AI Agent Tiering & Fallback Governance
Amendment to Section 9.x AI Strategy | Version 1.0 | March 2026

9.5.0 — Purpose
This section defines the routing logic between internal (self-hosted) and external (API) LLM agents. The platform uses a tiered approach: start with cheapest capable agent, escalate only when necessary, always have fallback.
Goals:
1.Cost optimization: Use internal LLM for 80%+ of workloads (cheaper)
2.Quality assurance: Escalate to external LLMs for complex tasks (higher quality)
3.Reliability: Always have fallback if any tier fails
4.User-invisible: Tiering happens behind the scenes (consistent UX)
This section binds to:
●Section 12.9 (Internal LLM Architecture) — Infrastructure specs
●Section 10.2 (Pricing) — Cost governance
●Section 12.5 (Observability) — Performance monitoring

9.5.1 — Agent Tier Definitions
Tier 1: Internal LLM (Primary — 80%+ Usage)
Model: Qwen 2.5-14B (self-hosted on A100 GPU)
Cost: ~$0.001 per 1M tokens (electricity + depreciation)
Use Cases:
●Activity suggestions (simple inference)
●Basic narration parsing (structured extraction)
●Route segment proposal (from voice input)
●Coverage clause Q&A (fine-tuned on policy corpus)
Strengths: Lowest cost, data sovereignty, GDPR compliant
Limitations: Weaker reasoning than GPT-4o/Claude Opus

Tier 2: External LLM (Cheap) — Fallback & Escalation
Models:
●Gemini Flash 2.0 (Google) — Free tier available, fast
●GPT-4o-mini (OpenAI) — $0.15 per 1M input tokens
Cost: ~$0.15-0.30 per 1M tokens
Use Cases:
●Complex narration parsing (ambiguity resolution)
●Multi-step reasoning (claim sequencing logic)
●Fallback when internal LLM unavailable
Strengths: Better reasoning than Tier 1, still cheap
Limitations: External API (data leaves platform), slower than internal

Tier 3: External LLM (Premium) — Specialty Tasks
Models:
●GPT-4o (OpenAI) — $2.50 per 1M input tokens
●Claude Sonnet 4 (Anthropic) — $3 per 1M input tokens
Cost: ~$2.50-5 per 1M tokens
Use Cases:
●Claim packet generation (requires professional language)
●Edge case handling (unusual policy clauses, complex incidents)
●Human-in-the-loop review (Founder disputes low confidence)
Strengths: Frontier reasoning, best quality
Limitations: Expensive, external API

9.5.2 — Routing Logic (Decision Tree)
[User Request] → [Classify Task]
    ↓
Is task simple? (activity suggestion, basic parsing)
    YES → Route to Tier 1 (Internal LLM)
    NO → Continue
    ↓
Is task medium complexity? (ambiguity resolution, multi-step)
    YES → Route to Tier 2 (Gemini Flash / GPT-4o-mini)
    NO → Continue
    ↓
Is task high complexity? (claim packet, edge case)
    YES → Route to Tier 3 (GPT-4o / Claude Sonnet)

Task Classification (automatic):
●Simple: Input <500 tokens, structured output, no reasoning required
●Medium: Input 500-2K tokens, requires disambiguation, multi-turn conversation
●Complex: Input >2K tokens, requires professional language, legal/insurance domain

9.5.3 — Confidence-Based Escalation
After Tier 1 response, check confidence score:
if tier1_confidence < 0.70:
    # Low confidence → escalate to Tier 2
    tier2_response = call_external_llm(tier2_model, prompt)
    if tier2_confidence < 0.85:
        # Still low → escalate to Tier 3
        tier3_response = call_external_llm(tier3_model, prompt)
        return tier3_response
    return tier2_response
return tier1_response

Confidence Thresholds (FOCL-configurable):
●Tier 1 → Tier 2 escalation: <0.70
●Tier 2 → Tier 3 escalation: <0.85
Events:
●ai_tier_escalated (logs: from_tier, to_tier, reason, confidence_score)

9.5.4 — Fallback Logic (Failure Handling)
Scenario 1: Tier 1 (Internal LLM) Down
Internal LLM unavailable (GPU failure, timeout)
    ↓
Fallback to Tier 2 (Gemini Flash)
    ↓
If Tier 2 down → Fallback to Tier 3 (GPT-4o)
    ↓
If all down → Degrade gracefully:
  - Save transcript (immutable)
  - Defer parsing (retry in 1 hour)
  - Show user: "Didn't quite get that. Want to try again?"

Events:
●ai_fallback_triggered (logs: failed_tier, fallback_tier, reason)

Scenario 2: External API Rate Limited
Tier 2/3 API returns 429 (rate limit exceeded)
    ↓
Try alternative model in same tier:
  - Gemini Flash → GPT-4o-mini
  - GPT-4o → Claude Sonnet
    ↓
If all models rate limited → Queue request (retry in 60 seconds)
    ↓
If user-facing request → Show: "High traffic right now. Please try again in a moment."


9.5.5 — Surge Behavior (PROTECTIVE Mode)
Under PROTECTIVE mode (Section 3.0):
Goal: Minimize cost during surge
Rules:
●Force Tier 1 only (internal LLM)
●Disable escalation (even if confidence < 0.70)
●Block Tier 3 (no premium API calls)
●Tier 2 fallback only (if Tier 1 completely down)
Trade-off: Lower quality AI responses during surge, but cost controlled.
User-facing: No change (quality may be slightly lower, but still functional)

9.5.6 — Cost Governance
Daily Spending Limits (FOCL-configured):
Tier	Model	Daily Limit	Alert Threshold
Tier 1	Internal LLM	N/A (fixed compute)	GPU utilization >90%
Tier 2	Gemini Flash / GPT-4o-mini	$100/day	>$80/day
Tier 3	GPT-4o / Claude Sonnet	$50/day	>$40/day
Hard Limits:
●If Tier 2 limit exceeded → Force Tier 1 (even for medium tasks)
●If Tier 3 limit exceeded → Block Tier 3 escalation
●Emit: ai_spending_limit_exceeded

9.5.7 — Observability
Key Metrics:
Metric	Type	Purpose
ai_requests_by_tier	Counter	Track Tier 1 vs Tier 2 vs Tier 3 usage
ai_cost_by_tier	Gauge	Daily spend per tier
ai_escalations_total	Counter	How often Tier 1 → Tier 2 → Tier 3
ai_fallback_total	Counter	How often fallback triggered
ai_confidence_score	Histogram	Confidence distribution per tier
Target Distribution:
●Tier 1: 80%+ of requests
●Tier 2: 15% of requests
●Tier 3: <5% of requests

